LADA: latent autoimmune diabetes in adults

For some context:

  • Type 1a diabetes - Type 1 diabetes in which there is demsonstrable autoantibody to either islet cells insulin or some other pancreas related antigen.

  • Type 1b diabetes - when the phenotype of Type 1 DM is present but there are no demonstrable autoantibodies.

  • LADA : #2020SBR-JUL/Q06 Adults who have clinical diabetes AND are positive for one or more autoantibodies but also have prolonged PRESERVATION of insulin secretion (i.e hence 'latent'). It's basically a slowly progressing form of Type 1 DM.

Ketosis-prone diabetes mellitus

Patient develops ketoacidosis but does not have the typical Type 1 DM phenotype.

Hypertensive encephalopathy

[!INFO] Illustration of altered cerebral autoregulation in hypertensive patients:

The minimum cerebral perfusion blood pressure is higher in hypertensive patients.

  • Pathogenesis: cerebral edema; MRI show oedema in white matter of parietooccipital regions which is similar to PRES syndrome.
  • Hypertensive encephalopathy usually occurs occurs in patients with longstanding hypertension who have a rapid and/or severe increase in blood pressure. (usually because they have stopped medication).
  • It is a diagnosis of exclusion. Lowering the MAP by 10-15% can dramatically improve symptoms and this retrospectively confirms the diagnosis.
  • Symptoms: Insidious onset (rather than acute onset like stroke but stroke must always be excluded)
    • Headache, nausea and vomiting.
    • Nonlocalizing neurologic symptoms: restlessness, confusion, progressing to seizures and coma.
  • Diagnosis: Diagnosis of exclusion but MRI with T2 weighted images will show the changes mentioned above.
  • Treatment: rapidly lower the mean arterial pressure by approximately 10 to 15 percent in the first hour, and by max. of 25 percent by the end of 24 hours.
    • Parentetal Clevidipine, nicardipine, labetalol and nitroprusside.

[!INFO] Acute hypertensive nephrosclerosis
Patients with severe hypertensive retinopathy and/or hypertensive encephalopathy often have acute hypertensive nephrosclerosis, leading to acute kidney injury, hematuria, and proteinuria (UpToDate)

Metformin associated lactic acidosis (MALA)

#2020SBR-JUL/Q13
Metformin induced / or associated lactic acidosis generally causes relatively high lactic acid levels. (>8)

Metformin mechanism:

Metformin

  • decreases insulin resistance,
  • decreases hepatic glucose output,
  • and enhances peripheral glucose uptake
  • Proposed mechanisms of action include enhanced suppression of gluconeogenesis by insulin, reduced glucagon-stimulated gluconeogenesis, and increased uptake of glucose by muscle and adipose cells

Management: (UpToDate)

  • There is not antidote for metformin poisoning. Management is mainly supportive to restore normal acid base balance.
  • Activated charcoal can be used for ACUTE ingestion.
  • Bicarbonate use is controversial. (Bicarbonate therapy has several side effects including vasolidation, left shift of Hb curve, and decreased myocardial contractility). Therefore, when used, it's used only to keep the pH > 7.1; not to normalize pH.
  • For pH < 7.0, Lactate > 20, or refractory acidosis -> dialysis can be used.

  • Drugs: NSAIDS (including COX2 selective ones), cephalosporins, PPIs and many other antibiotics.[[General Medicine 4#Q 5 Adverse effects of PPI use.]]
  • Classical clinical features:
    • Triad of fever, rash and eosinphilia and non specific symptoms of AKI.
    • Usually no significant proteinuria but can be present.
    • Can present with proteinuria if the disease is NSAID induced.
  • Investigation : Urine white cell casts, eosinophiluria (but this is not sensitive or specific).
  • Definitive diagnosis requires renal biopsy.
  • Treatment: ‚ùóCan progress to ESKD; early recognition and cessation of the offending drug is required. If symptoms to no resolve within a few days, corticosteroid therapy.

Neuroleptic: Any type of drug affecting the CNS.
Serotonin syndrome: caused by a subset of drugs causing NMS. (SSRI, SNRI, MAOI, TCA, [[Toxicology#MDMA|Ecstasy]])

üìëCoeliac disease

üìëSymptoms

Most commonly asymptomatic; but patients will show signs of malabsorption.
Many and will be diagnosed upon evaluation for macrocytic anaemia. (due to malabsorption).

üìëComplications

  • Osteoporosis
  • parasaesthesia, ataxia, polyneuropathy.
  • Associated with autoimmune diseases: IBD, primary biliary cholangitis, chonic liver disease, ILD, epilepsy.

Tropical sprue

Disease of unknown aetiology, occurring in tropical regions and causing chronic diarrhoea with malabsorption. (particularly B9 and B12).
Probably caused by bacterial overgrowth which results in structural damage to the small intestine.

The major histologic findings are shortened, blunted villi and elongated crypts with increased inflammatory cells in the lamina propria

Treatment can be with tetratycline but even with this, recurrences are common.
